Second Lady Karen Pence will be traveling to Tallinn, Estonia; Tbilisi, Georgia; and Podgorica, Montenegro from July 29 to August 2, 2017. In Tallinn, she will visit a medical center and participate in a roundtable discussion with art therapists. Art therapy is a growing discipline in Estonia, with approximately 45 practitioners in the country. In Tbilisi, Georgia, Mrs. Pence will meet with patients of an art therapy program and view their artwork. She will also engage in a roundtable discussion with art therapists. Art therapy is an emerging profession in Georgia, with only a few professionally trained art therapists. Additionally, Mrs. Pence will visit an exhibit of paintings inspired by Robert Frost's poems at the Tbilisi History Museum Karvasla. In Podgorica, Montenegro, she will tour a honey farm and learn about a local family's beekeeping business. Following this, Mrs. Pence will take part in a cultural tour of Lake Skadar. Art therapy is a mental health profession that utilizes the creative process of art making to enhance the well-being of individuals of all ages. It helps individuals explore their feelings, manage behavior and addictions, develop social skills, reduce anxiety, and increase self-esteem.